Note: ================================================================
Note: LaTeX Translation Emitter
Note: ================================================================
Note: High-level orchestration for LaTeX <-> HIR translation.
Note: Provides convenience functions for round-trip translation.
Note: ================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/latex/latex_lexer.runa" as LaTeXLexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/latex/latex_parser.runa" as LaTeXParser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/latex/latex_to_hir.runa" as LaTeXToHIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/latex/hir_to_latex.runa" as HIRToLaTeX
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as ListCore

Note: ================================================================
Note: LaTeX Source to HIR Translation
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Forward leg of the LaTeX <-> HIR pipeline. Strict mode: returns 0 on
any lex/parse/translate error so callers don't proceed with partial
HIR. The `_with_errors` variant below preserves diagnostics for
reporting.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a fresh lexer over source_code, tokenizes, and bails on lexer
errors. Creates a parser over the tokens, parses to AST, bails on
parser errors. Creates a translator and produces HIR, bails if the
translator reports has_errors. Otherwise returns the HIR module root.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Cold path - one full pipeline per source file. Allocates lexer, parser,
translator, plus all intermediate token/AST/HIR structures.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Treats source_code as untrusted. All error conditions are funneled
through stage-local error lists rather than crashing; null returns
indicate "do not proceed" to the caller.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "latex_to_hir" that takes source_code as String returns Integer:
    Note: Step 1: Lexical analysis
    Let lexer_ptr be proc create_lexer from LaTeXLexer with source_code
    proc tokenize from LaTeXLexer with lexer_ptr

    Note: Check for lexer errors
    Let lexer_errors be proc get_errors from LaTeXLexer with lexer_ptr
    Let error_count be proc get_list_size from ListCore with lexer_errors

    If error_count is greater than 0:
        Note: Lexer errors present, return null
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 2: Parsing
    Let tokens be proc get_tokens from LaTeXLexer with lexer_ptr
    Let parser_ptr be proc create_parser from LaTeXParser with tokens
    Let ast be proc parse from LaTeXParser with parser_ptr

    Note: Check for parser errors
    Let parser_errors be proc get_errors from LaTeXParser with parser_ptr
    Set error_count to proc get_list_size from ListCore with parser_errors

    If error_count is greater than 0:
        Note: Parser errors present, return null
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 3: Translation to HIR
    Let translator_ptr be proc create_translator from LaTeXToHIR
    Let hir_module be proc translate from LaTeXToHIR with translator_ptr, ast

    Note: Check for translation errors
    Let has_errors be proc has_errors from LaTeXToHIR with translator_ptr

    If has_errors is equal to 1:
        Note: Translation errors present, return null
        Return 0
    End If

    Return hir_module
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: HIR to LaTeX Code Generation
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Backend leg of the pipeline; converts HIR back to LaTeX source. Strict
mode: returns empty string on any backend error so callers can detect
failure without examining a separate error list.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates the HIR -> LaTeX backend, invokes translate, then checks the
backend's has_errors flag. Returns the empty string on error,
otherwise the generated LaTeX source.
@End Implementation

Process called "hir_to_latex" that takes hir_module as Integer returns String:
    Note: Create backend and generate LaTeX code
    Let backend_ptr be proc create_backend from HIRToLaTeX
    Let latex_code be proc translate from HIRToLaTeX with backend_ptr, hir_module

    Note: Check for backend errors
    Let has_errors be proc has_errors from HIRToLaTeX with backend_ptr

    If has_errors is equal to 1:
        Note: Backend errors present, return empty string
        Return ""
    End If

    Return latex_code
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Round-Trip Translation (LaTeX -> HIR -> LaTeX)
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
End-to-end fidelity test entry point: ingest LaTeX source, lower to
HIR, then regenerate LaTeX source from that HIR. Used by golden-output
tests to verify that the LaTeX <-> HIR translation preserves meaning.
Empty string on forward-leg failure prevents feeding null HIR to the
backend.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Chains latex_to_hir then hir_to_latex. If latex_to_hir returned 0
(failure), returns the empty string immediately.
@End Implementation

Process called "latex_roundtrip" that takes source_code as String returns String:
    Note: Translate to HIR
    Let hir_module be proc latex_to_hir from source_code

    If hir_module is equal to 0:
        Note: Translation to HIR failed
        Return ""
    End If

    Note: Translate back to LaTeX
    Let latex_code be proc hir_to_latex from hir_module

    Return latex_code
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Error Reporting Helpers
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Diagnostic-preserving variant of latex_to_hir. Unlike the strict form,
this collects errors from every stage (lex, parse, translate) plus
translator warnings into a single output list so the caller (CLI,
LSP, golden test runner) can present them all to the user. Continues
past lexer/parser errors when possible to maximize the diagnostic
yield from a single run.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a fresh List for the unified errors. Tokenizes; prefixes any
lexer errors with "Lexer: " and appends them. Parses; prefixes any
parser errors with "Parser: " and appends them. If lexer or parser
errors were found, returns 0 (translation would be meaningless), but
the errors list is still written out via the errors_out pointer.
Otherwise translates, prefixes translator errors with "Translator: "
and warnings with "Warning: ", and writes the unified list before
returning the HIR module (or 0 if translation produced errors).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Cold path - one pipeline per source file. Extra cost over latex_to_hir
is the string_concat per error/warning to add the stage prefix.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Treats source_code as untrusted. errors_out is a caller-provided
output pointer; this proc writes the new error-list pointer at offset
0 of that location. Caller owns the resulting list.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "latex_to_hir_with_errors" that takes source_code as String, errors_out as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Step 1: Lexical analysis
    Let lexer_ptr be proc create_lexer from LaTeXLexer with source_code
    proc tokenize from LaTeXLexer with lexer_ptr

    Let all_errors be proc create_list from ListCore

    Note: Collect lexer errors
    Let lexer_errors be proc get_errors from LaTeXLexer with lexer_ptr
    Let error_count be proc get_list_size from ListCore with lexer_errors
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than error_count:
        Let error_msg be proc get_from_list from ListCore with lexer_errors, index
        Let prefixed_msg be proc string_concat from StringCore with "Lexer: ", error_msg
        proc add_to_list from ListCore with all_errors, prefixed_msg
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Note: Continue to parsing even with lexer errors (for better error reporting)
    Let tokens be proc get_tokens from LaTeXLexer with lexer_ptr
    Let parser_ptr be proc create_parser from LaTeXParser with tokens
    Let ast be proc parse from LaTeXParser with parser_ptr

    Note: Collect parser errors
    Let parser_errors be proc get_errors from LaTeXParser with parser_ptr
    Set error_count to proc get_list_size from ListCore with parser_errors
    Set index to 0

    While index is less than error_count:
        Set error_msg to proc get_from_list from ListCore with parser_errors, index
        Set prefixed_msg to proc string_concat from StringCore with "Parser: ", error_msg
        proc add_to_list from ListCore with all_errors, prefixed_msg
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Note: Continue to translation if no critical errors
    Let total_errors be proc get_list_size from ListCore with all_errors

    If total_errors is greater than 0:
        proc write_integer from Memory with errors_out, 0, all_errors
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 3: Translation to HIR
    Let translator_ptr be proc create_translator from LaTeXToHIR
    Let hir_module be proc translate from LaTeXToHIR with translator_ptr, ast

    Note: Collect translation errors
    Let translation_errors be proc get_errors from LaTeXToHIR with translator_ptr
    Set error_count to proc get_list_size from ListCore with translation_errors
    Set index to 0

    While index is less than error_count:
        Set error_msg to proc get_from_list from ListCore with translation_errors, index
        Set prefixed_msg to proc string_concat from StringCore with "Translator: ", error_msg
        proc add_to_list from ListCore with all_errors, prefixed_msg
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Note: Collect translation warnings
    Let translation_warnings be proc get_warnings from LaTeXToHIR with translator_ptr
    Let warning_count be proc get_list_size from ListCore with translation_warnings
    Set index to 0

    While index is less than warning_count:
        Let warning_msg be proc get_from_list from ListCore with translation_warnings, index
        Set prefixed_msg to proc string_concat from StringCore with "Warning: ", warning_msg
        proc add_to_list from ListCore with all_errors, prefixed_msg
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Note: Write errors to output parameter
    proc write_integer from Memory with errors_out, 0, all_errors

    Set total_errors to proc get_list_size from ListCore with all_errors

    If total_errors is greater than 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return hir_module
End Process

@Reasoning:
Diagnostic-preserving variant of hir_to_latex. Collects backend errors
into a unified list and writes them out via the errors_out pointer so
the caller can present them.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Runs the backend, then iterates backend errors prefixing each with
"Backend: " before adding to the unified list. Writes the list to
errors_out, returns the empty string if any backend errors were found,
otherwise the generated LaTeX source.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
errors_out is a caller-provided output pointer; this proc writes the
new error-list pointer at offset 0 of that location. Caller owns the
resulting list.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "hir_to_latex_with_errors" that takes hir_module as Integer, errors_out as Integer returns String:
    Let backend_ptr be proc create_backend from HIRToLaTeX
    Let latex_code be proc translate from HIRToLaTeX with backend_ptr, hir_module

    Let all_errors be proc create_list from ListCore

    Note: Collect backend errors
    Let backend_errors be proc get_errors from HIRToLaTeX with backend_ptr
    Let error_count be proc get_list_size from ListCore with backend_errors
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than error_count:
        Let error_msg be proc get_from_list from ListCore with backend_errors, index
        Let prefixed_msg be proc string_concat from StringCore with "Backend: ", error_msg
        proc add_to_list from ListCore with all_errors, prefixed_msg
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Note: Write errors to output parameter
    proc write_integer from Memory with errors_out, 0, all_errors

    Let total_errors be proc get_list_size from ListCore with all_errors

    If total_errors is greater than 0:
        Return ""
    End If

    Return latex_code
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Validation and Formatting
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Boolean syntactic-validity check: does the source lex and parse
without errors? Does not invoke the translator because well-formedness
is independent of HIR mapping coverage. Used by IDE tooling and the
test runner for cheap validity gating.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Runs the lexer and bails with 0 on any lexer error. Runs the parser
and bails with 0 on any parser error. Otherwise returns 1.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Roughly half the cost of latex_to_hir because it skips translation.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "validate_latex" that takes source_code as String returns Integer:
    Note: Validate LaTeX by attempting to parse it
    Let lexer_ptr be proc create_lexer from LaTeXLexer with source_code
    proc tokenize from LaTeXLexer with lexer_ptr

    Let lexer_errors be proc get_errors from LaTeXLexer with lexer_ptr
    Let error_count be proc get_list_size from ListCore with lexer_errors

    If error_count is greater than 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let tokens be proc get_tokens from LaTeXLexer with lexer_ptr
    Let parser_ptr be proc create_parser from LaTeXParser with tokens
    Let ast be proc parse from LaTeXParser with parser_ptr

    Let parser_errors be proc get_errors from LaTeXParser with parser_ptr
    Set error_count to proc get_list_size from ListCore with parser_errors

    If error_count is greater than 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Valid LaTeX
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Source reformatter implemented as a round-trip. Lowering to HIR
discards optional whitespace/structural variations; regenerating from
HIR produces a canonical form. Equivalent to running latex_roundtrip
under a different name.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to latex_roundtrip; preserved as a separate entry for IDE
tooling that wants a "format this file" command distinct from a
"verify round-trip fidelity" command.
@End Implementation

Process called "format_latex" that takes source_code as String returns String:
    Note: Format LaTeX by round-trip translation
    Note: This normalizes the code structure
    Return proc latex_roundtrip from source_code
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Utility Functions
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Convenience extractor for the standard LaTeX preamble commands (\title,
\author, \date). Useful for indexing tools and document-listing UIs
that want a quick summary without rendering the full document.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Lowers source to HIR; on failure returns an empty list rather than 0
so callers can iterate the result unconditionally. Allocates a list
and walks the HIR with extract_metadata_from_hir to populate it with
key/value pairs.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_document_info" that takes source_code as String returns Integer:
    Note: Extract document metadata (title, author, date, etc.) from LaTeX source
    Let hir_module be proc latex_to_hir from source_code

    If hir_module is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_list from ListCore
    End If

    Note: Create info dictionary to store metadata
    Let info_dict be proc create_list from ListCore

    Note: Traverse HIR to find document metadata commands
    Note: Look for nodes representing \title{}, \author{}, \date{} commands
    proc extract_metadata_from_hir with info_dict, hir_module

    Return info_dict
End Process

@Reasoning:
Recursive HIR walker for get_document_info. Visits every node looking
for command nodes whose name matches a known metadata command (title,
author, date), extracting the content of each match into the
caller-supplied dictionary.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 immediately on a null node. Reads the node type at offset 8
and the command_name at offset 16. If the command_name is non-null and
matches "title", "author", or "date", appends a (key, content) pair to
info_dict. Then reads the children list pointer and recurses into each
child by index.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) in the HIR node count. Tail-recursive over siblings but uses real
recursion across parent/child boundaries; recursion depth is bounded
by the document's nesting depth (typically <20).
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "extract_metadata_from_hir" that takes info_dict as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Recursively traverse HIR to extract document metadata

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get node type to determine what kind of node this is
    Let node_type be proc get_int_at_offset from Memory with node, 8

    Note: Check if this is a command node (e.g., \title, \author, \date)
    Note: LaTeX commands in HIR typically have a command_name field
    Let command_name be proc get_string_at_offset from Memory with node, 16

    If command_name is not equal to 0:
        Note: Check for metadata commands
        Let is_title be proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "title"
        Let is_author be proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "author"
        Let is_date be proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "date"

        If is_title is equal to 1:
            Let content be proc get_command_content from node
            proc list_append from ListCore with info_dict, proc create_pair with "title", content
        End If

        If is_author is equal to 1:
            Set content to proc get_command_content from node
            proc list_append from ListCore with info_dict, proc create_pair with "author", content
        End If

        If is_date is equal to 1:
            Set content to proc get_command_content from node
            proc list_append from ListCore with info_dict, proc create_pair with "date", content
        End If
    End If

    Note: Recursively traverse child nodes
    Let children be proc get_children_list from Memory with node
    If children is not equal to 0:
        Let child_count be proc get_list_size from ListCore with children
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than child_count:
            Let child be proc get_list_item from ListCore with children, i
            proc extract_metadata_from_hir with info_dict, child
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Helper used by metadata, citation, and label extractors to pull the
text payload out of a LaTeX command HIR node. Centralizes the offset
convention so future HIR layout changes only need to update this proc.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the content_node pointer at offset 24; if null, returns the empty
string. Otherwise reads the text string at offset 0 of the content
node; returns it if non-null, else the empty string.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_command_content" that takes node as Integer returns String:
    Note: Extract text content from a LaTeX command node
    Let content_node be proc get_int_at_offset from Memory with node, 24
    If content_node is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If

    Note: Get text from content node
    Let text be proc get_string_at_offset from Memory with content_node, 0
    If text is not equal to 0:
        Return text
    End If

    Return ""
End Process

@Reasoning:
Builds a fixed-shape (key, value) record used to populate the metadata
list. Inlined here rather than using a generic Pair type to keep the
metadata storage layout predictable for downstream consumers.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 16 bytes; writes the key string at offset 0 and the value
string at offset 8. Caller owns the resulting pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_pair" that takes key as String, value as String returns Integer:
    Note: Create a key-value pair structure
    Let pair be proc allocate from Memory with 16
    proc set_string_at_offset from Memory with pair, 0, key
    proc set_string_at_offset from Memory with pair, 8, value
    Return pair
End Process

@Reasoning:
Extracts every citation key referenced in a LaTeX document so callers
(bibliography linters, cross-reference checkers) can verify them
against a .bib file. Recognizes the five most common natbib/biblatex
citation commands.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Lowers source to HIR; on failure returns an empty list rather than 0
so callers can iterate unconditionally. Allocates a result list and
walks the HIR with extract_citations_from_hir.
@End Implementation

Process called "extract_citations" that takes source_code as String returns Integer:
    Note: Extract all citation keys from LaTeX document
    Let hir_module be proc latex_to_hir from source_code

    If hir_module is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_list from ListCore
    End If

    Note: Create list to store citation keys
    Let citations be proc create_list from ListCore

    Note: Traverse HIR to find all citation nodes (\cite, \citep, \citet, etc.)
    proc extract_citations_from_hir with citations, hir_module

    Return citations
End Process

@Reasoning:
Recursive HIR walker for extract_citations. Recognizes the natbib/
biblatex command family (\cite, \citep, \citet, \citealt, \citealp);
other custom citation commands would require extending this list.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 on a null node. Reads command_name at offset 16; if it
matches any of the five known citation commands, extracts the
citation key via get_command_content and appends it to the result
list. Recurses into the children list at the HIR-defined offset.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) in HIR node count with a small constant per node (five string
comparisons in the worst case).
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "extract_citations_from_hir" that takes citations as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Recursively traverse HIR to find citation commands

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get command name if this is a command node
    Let command_name be proc get_string_at_offset from Memory with node, 16

    If command_name is not equal to 0:
        Note: Check if this is a citation command
        Let is_cite be proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "cite"
        Let is_citep be proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "citep"
        Let is_citet be proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "citet"
        Let is_citealt be proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "citealt"
        Let is_citealp be proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "citealp"

        If is_cite is equal to 1:
            Let citation_key be proc get_command_content from node
            proc list_append from ListCore with citations, citation_key
        End If

        If is_citep is equal to 1:
            Set citation_key to proc get_command_content from node
            proc list_append from ListCore with citations, citation_key
        End If

        If is_citet is equal to 1:
            Set citation_key to proc get_command_content from node
            proc list_append from ListCore with citations, citation_key
        End If

        If is_citealt is equal to 1:
            Set citation_key to proc get_command_content from node
            proc list_append from ListCore with citations, citation_key
        End If

        If is_citealp is equal to 1:
            Set citation_key to proc get_command_content from node
            proc list_append from ListCore with citations, citation_key
        End If
    End If

    Note: Recursively traverse child nodes
    Let children be proc get_children_list from Memory with node
    If children is not equal to 0:
        Let child_count be proc get_list_size from ListCore with children
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than child_count:
            Let child be proc get_list_item from ListCore with children, i
            proc extract_citations_from_hir with citations, child
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Counterpart to extract_citations for the \label command. Used by
cross-reference checkers to ensure every \ref and \pageref points at
a known label.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Lowers source to HIR; on failure returns an empty list. Allocates a
result list and walks the HIR with extract_labels_from_hir.
@End Implementation

Process called "extract_labels" that takes source_code as String returns Integer:
    Note: Extract all label identifiers from LaTeX document
    Let hir_module be proc latex_to_hir from source_code

    If hir_module is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_list from ListCore
    End If

    Note: Create list to store labels
    Let labels be proc create_list from ListCore

    Note: Traverse HIR to find all label nodes (\label{})
    proc extract_labels_from_hir with labels, hir_module

    Return labels
End Process

@Reasoning:
Recursive HIR walker for extract_labels. Only the single command name
"label" is recognized; LaTeX has no other standard label-declaring
commands.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 on a null node. Reads command_name at offset 16; if it
equals "label", appends the label name (via get_command_content) to
the result list. Recurses into children.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) in HIR node count.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "extract_labels_from_hir" that takes labels as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Recursively traverse HIR to find label commands

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get command name if this is a command node
    Let command_name be proc get_string_at_offset from Memory with node, 16

    If command_name is not equal to 0:
        Note: Check if this is a label command
        Let is_label be proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "label"

        If is_label is equal to 1:
            Let label_name be proc get_command_content from node
            proc list_append from ListCore with labels, label_name
        End If
    End If

    Note: Recursively traverse child nodes
    Let children be proc get_children_list from Memory with node
    If children is not equal to 0:
        Let child_count be proc get_list_size from ListCore with children
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than child_count:
            Let child be proc get_list_item from ListCore with children, i
            proc extract_labels_from_hir with labels, child
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Return 1
End Process
